01:20:54.570 --> 01:20:56.010
- I can't really.

01:20:56.010 --> 01:20:58.050
And you're asking a
few questions there.

01:20:58.050 --> 01:21:00.660
You know, there's the
question about what percentage

01:21:00.660 --> 01:21:02.950
of patients with repeated
use wind up getting addicted

01:21:02.950 --> 01:21:06.150
and how many don't.

01:21:06.150 --> 01:21:08.010
It's very difficult to say.

01:21:08.010 --> 01:21:10.530
What we do know is
the common pathway

01:21:10.530 --> 01:21:14.070
to becoming addicted to
opioids is repeated use.

01:21:14.070 --> 01:21:15.840
And it doesn't really
make a difference

01:21:15.840 --> 01:21:18.690
if you're repeating
use because it's fun,

01:21:18.690 --> 01:21:20.760
or you're repeating
use because you're

01:21:20.760 --> 01:21:23.550
self-medicating dysphoria.

01:21:23.550 --> 01:21:27.690
Maybe you're in a community with
a lack of economic opportunity,

01:21:27.690 --> 01:21:29.030
and there's despair.

01:21:29.030 --> 01:21:31.290
And it's making you feel better.

01:21:31.290 --> 01:21:34.985
Or you're repeating use because
a doctor told you to take it.

01:21:34.985 --> 01:21:36.360
It really does
make a difference.

01:21:36.360 --> 01:21:39.500
Once you repeat use regularly,
you can become addicted.

01:21:39.500 --> 01:21:42.984
And although we don't have
good data on the development

01:21:42.984 --> 01:21:44.400
of addiction with
repeated use, we

01:21:44.400 --> 01:21:47.550
do have good data on the
development of long-term use

01:21:47.550 --> 01:21:48.840
in pain patients.

01:21:48.840 --> 01:21:52.710
And we know that a patient
who takes an opioid every day

01:21:52.710 --> 01:21:57.240
for 10 days, 1 in 5
become long-term users.

01:21:57.240 --> 01:21:59.640
And if the patients are
prescribed opioids every day

01:21:59.640 --> 01:22:04.640
for 30 days, about 40% are
still on opioids a year later.

