I don't think anybody
who sort of knows

01:23:30.400 --> 01:23:32.770
the policing literature
thought that technology

01:23:32.770 --> 01:23:34.090
was going to be the answer.

01:23:34.090 --> 01:23:38.290
We thought it would actually
be more related to issues

01:23:38.290 --> 01:23:39.135
of transparency.

01:23:39.135 --> 01:23:41.260
The other thing that we
don't know from that study,

01:23:41.260 --> 01:23:43.300
of course, is officer
discretion of when

01:23:43.300 --> 01:23:45.010
the camera is on or
off, which is also

01:23:45.010 --> 01:23:49.000
a big deal in the meta-review
of these body camera studies.

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:52.750
When officers have no discretion
about when the camera is on,

01:23:52.750 --> 01:23:53.750
we see positive effects.

01:23:53.750 --> 01:23:56.124
And we tend to see null effects
when they have discretion

01:23:56.124 --> 01:23:58.450
about when they can turn it
on or off or fudge with it

01:23:58.450 --> 01:23:59.330
a little bit.

01:23:59.330 --> 01:24:01.180
So that's my take on it.

01:24:01.180 --> 01:24:03.430
You know, I don't think one
study is going to make it.

01:24:06.106 --> 01:24:07.730
- Hi my name is Sarah
[? Altschuller ?]

01:24:07.730 --> 01:24:10.430
And I'm from Northeastern.

01:24:10.430 --> 01:24:16.316
I also have a question
for Andrew Papachristos.

01:24:16.316 --> 01:24:17.641
And I'll say I'm a humanist.

01:24:17.641 --> 01:24:19.640
So I'm wondering a little
bit about the language

01:24:19.640 --> 01:24:22.460
and the kind of paradigms
that you're using and thinking

01:24:22.460 --> 01:24:24.820
specifically about--

01:24:24.820 --> 01:24:27.420
I understand that we
all speak in analogies.

01:24:27.420 --> 01:24:31.130
So I'm just wondering about
the use of AIDS and HIV

01:24:31.130 --> 01:24:33.980
as a paradigm and,
specifically, about the move

01:24:33.980 --> 01:24:37.010
to kind of think about
contagious disease

01:24:37.010 --> 01:24:39.770
as a paradigm, as a kind
of metaphor for thinking

01:24:39.770 --> 01:24:40.920
about gun violence.

01:24:40.920 --> 01:24:43.100
And I understand the sort
of rhetorical efficacy.

01:24:43.100 --> 01:24:45.830
So I'm also asking about
what potential pitfalls are

01:24:45.830 --> 01:24:46.690
of doing that.

01:24:46.690 --> 01:24:50.300
- Well, the pitfalls, of course,
those other epidemics also

01:24:50.300 --> 01:24:52.560
deal with super
vulnerable populations.

01:24:52.560 --> 01:24:54.080
So I get that.

01:24:54.080 --> 01:24:57.287
What I'm actually trying
to work against is the--

01:24:57.287 --> 01:24:59.120
I don't want to say
baseless, but more empty

01:24:59.120 --> 01:25:00.320
political rhetoric.

01:25:00.320 --> 01:25:03.560
So if anybody is looking for a
master's thesis in this room,

01:25:03.560 --> 01:25:06.350
March, there's going to
be a call for the National

01:25:06.350 --> 01:25:10.550
Guard in Chicago after the first
kid that's walking to school

01:25:10.550 --> 01:25:12.950
is sort of shot and killed.

01:25:12.950 --> 01:25:16.730
And in fact, what I'm trying to
do with the metaphors is really

01:25:16.730 --> 01:25:21.680
trying to make people understand
that the majority of victims

01:25:21.680 --> 01:25:24.920
are not the kid going to school
or the grandma going to church,

01:25:24.920 --> 01:25:28.016
but young men of color
who have criminal records.

01:25:28.016 --> 01:25:30.140
And the media needs to be
held accountable, as well

01:25:30.140 --> 01:25:32.790
as the academics and the public
health officials and everybody

01:25:32.790 --> 01:25:33.290
else.

01:25:33.290 --> 01:25:35.990
But specifically, it's to
remove the discussion out

01:25:35.990 --> 01:25:38.470
of the criminal
justice language.

01:25:38.470 --> 01:25:40.800
And that's the big jump.

01:25:40.800 --> 01:25:41.300
Right?

01:25:41.300 --> 01:25:43.280
Because we're not going
to arrest ourselves out

01:25:43.280 --> 01:25:43.946
of this problem.

01:25:43.946 --> 01:25:46.100
And in fact, any police
chief in this country

01:25:46.100 --> 01:25:47.390
will tell you you're not
going to arrest yourself out

01:25:47.390 --> 01:25:49.080
of a gun violence problem.

01:25:49.080 --> 01:25:50.780
And so it's just
a conscious effort

01:25:50.780 --> 01:25:53.060
to try to move it more to
the public health problem,

01:25:53.060 --> 01:25:55.640
but also, from the data
analytics perspective,

01:25:55.640 --> 01:25:57.710
to know that, as
we've seen here,

01:25:57.710 --> 01:26:00.770
we can use similar techniques
with highly vulnerable

01:26:00.770 --> 01:26:03.621
populations in ways that are
moral, in ways that are just,

01:26:03.621 --> 01:26:05.120
and in ways that
can be transparent.

01:26:05.120 --> 01:26:06.770
It can also go horribly wrong.

01:26:06.770 --> 01:26:09.500
But there are ways we can reduce
Hep-C with needle exchange

01:26:09.500 --> 01:26:11.840
programs or condom
distribution or working

01:26:11.840 --> 01:26:14.870
with men who have sex with men
and drop rates of infection

01:26:14.870 --> 01:26:18.170
very dramatically and work
with these populations

01:26:18.170 --> 01:26:20.820
and treat them first
and foremost as victims.

01:26:20.820 --> 01:26:22.305
So that's my intentional use.

01:26:22.305 --> 01:26:23.930
But other pitfalls
I already mentioned.

01:26:23.930 --> 01:26:27.950
It clearly can also become
racialized or politicized.

01:26:27.950 --> 01:26:31.143
Like the word gun
itself is politicized.

